description: Facial features, particularly the mouth, lips, and nose, are often mentioned in the context of emotions, actions, or physical sensations.
The token "nose" often represents a body part, and is frequently used in contexts where the object or character is experiencing a physical sensation, action, or condition affecting the nose.
Words related to sounds or bodily functions, often involving the mouth or nose.
Words related to the mouth, nose, and throat, often used in various contexts, including health, everyday activities, and figurative expressions.
Conjunctions connecting words, particularly in medical contexts, often related to the ear, nose, and throat, or used to describe symptoms and conditions.
Texts describing human body parts, mostly facial features such as nose, eyes, ears, and also mentioning various beauty procedures, surgeries, and conditions affecting these body parts.

Words or parts of words that start with "sn" or "sne" often related to actions, sounds or movements of the nose or mouth, such as sneezing, snoring, or snacking, or sometimes unrelated words that happen to start with this sequence of letters.
A variety of nasal and sinus-related words and phrases, often associated with symptoms, conditions, or treatment of respiratory issues, such as congestion, runny nose, and allergies.
Facial features, often describing a person's eyes, but also face, skin, hair, nose, mouth, or other facial attributes.
References to the nose, often literally or figuratively, in various contexts, including physical descriptions, idiomatic expressions, and medical conditions.
Parts of the face, such as the face, eyes, nose, and facial features, often used to describe people's emotions or appearance in various situations.
The token is part of a word that is related to aircraft, specifically parts of a plane such as the wing, tail, or nose, or other words that describe elements of an aircraft.
Words related to parts of the head, specifically the mouth, nose, tongue, and throat, often in medical, descriptive, or everyday contexts.

Various tokens often indicating direction, movement, or relationship between entities, such as "to", "of", "at", "from", "with", and "in", as well as some nouns representing objects or concepts that can be directed or pointed towards, like "finger", "camera", "arrow", "gun", and "nose".
The token "sn" often appears at the start of words that begin with "sn", many of which are related to sounds, smells, or noses.
Texts related to nasal passages, sinuses, and allergy-relieving products, often mentioning the nose and other parts of the head or face.
Texts often relate to ear, nose, and throat issues, including infections, hearing problems, and treatments, with a focus on otolaryngology.

The selected tokens often appear to be function words or articles that are part of a larger phrase or sentence, but the most distinctive pattern is that many of the highlighted tokens are part of a body part or bodily action, such as "hand", "finger", "foot", "arm", "leg", "skin", or "nose".

Ordinal directions (left, right) or body parts (nose, side) are used to specify football positions or locations on a field, while words such as "play" or "starting" suggest football strategy or roles.
The text often contains words related to the nose, sinuses, or related symptoms such as congestion, sneezing, or runny nose.
